    id: "fifa-looks-broken-by-every-modern",
    title: "FIFA looks broken by every modern governance standard",
    date: "2026-06-23",
    image: "images/fifa-looks-broken-by-every-modern.jpg",
    categories: ["society"],
    teaser:
      "And that may be exactly why it works.",
    content: [
      "High prices. Opaque leadership. Consumers only have weak leverage. Limited accountability.  And yet, every four years, that same structure helps stage the most unifying global event on Earth.  That is the paradox.",
      "## The FIFA Paradox: Why Isolation Creates Value",
      "If you judge FIFA by modern corporate governance standards, it looks like a failure.",
      "High prices. Opaque leadership. Weak consumer leverage. Limited accountability.",
      "And yet, every four years, that same structure helps stage the most unifying global event on Earth.",
      "That is the paradox.",
      "## 1. FIFA Is an Emotional Landlord",
      "Most companies try to build community around a product.",
      "FIFA starts somewhere stronger: identity.",
      "It does not create the emotional asset. It controls the arena where that asset gets expressed.",
      "Fans are not really buying FIFA. They are buying access to country, memory, family, rivalry, and belonging.",
      "That makes the normal rules of consumer power weaker. You can boycott a product. It is much harder to boycott your own national identity.",
      "2. Insulation Is the Product.",
      "Here is the uncomfortable point: FIFA’s insulation is not incidental to its power. It is part of the operating model.",
      "A normal global corporation is exposed to shareholder pressure, activist campaigns, regional politics, and brand-risk spirals.",
      "FIFA is different. Its distance from any single public, government, or shareholder base lets it function as a neutral stage.",
      "That does not excuse bad governance. Insulation is not impunity.",
      "But it does explain why the institution can host a tournament that pulls together countries divided by politics, economics, history, and war.",
      "## The Executive Lesson",
      "Most brands overestimate the power of purpose.",
      "They try to manufacture culture, then wonder why the market does not care.",
      "The stronger play is different: build infrastructure around an identity that already exists.",
      "Transactional brands compete on price and features. They are easy to replace.",
      "Community brands organize shared interests. They are harder to disrupt.",
      "Identity brands attach to who people already are. They are structurally resilient.",
      "FIFA sits in the third category.",
      "Its value is not that people trust the institution. Its value is that people need the stage.",
      "## The Bottom Line",
      "FIFA does not succeed despite its isolation.  It succeeds, in part, because that isolation protects the only thing big enough to survive global fragmentation: shared identity under a single set of rules.",
      "Where do you draw the line? Can a normal enterprise ever build this kind of identity-driven resilience, or is it reserved for sports, nations, and institutions that sit above the market?",
    ],
